<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-06-13T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-06-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="96" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d96">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/2434</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-06-13T13:00:00+08:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 13, 1916, 1 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Official statement reported given out in Japan to the effect that
                            foreigners in China desire more protection has no foundation. Conditions
                                <pb facs="0161" n="85" xml:id="pg_85"/> here are again perfectly
                            normal, with no apprehension on the part of foreigners and with a
                            feeling of confidence in assured realization of economic political
                            progress under the Republic.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>